          "title": "The priestly portions — duty, not privilege",
          "body": "Moses' instructions in verses 12-15 are easy to read as mere procedural instruction following a crisis, but their placement is deliberate. Immediately after the deaths, the surviving priests are directed to eat. The grain offering is most holy and must be eaten beside the altar (10:12-13); the wave breast and contribution thigh may be eaten in any clean place by the entire priestly household (10:14-15). This is not comfort food. Eating the offering is part of the atonement mechanism — particularly for the sin offering, as Moses will argue sharply in verses 16-17. The priest who eats the most holy portions is not enjoying a perquisite; he is completing the atonement transaction on behalf of the congregation. Peter Davids' work on purity and priesthood in the Second Temple context illuminates how completely the priestly eating was integrated into the sacrificial logic: the offering was not finished until the prescribed portions were consumed in the prescribed place. Eleazar and Ithamar's failure to eat the sin offering (10:16) is therefore not a minor oversight — it is an incomplete atonement for the congregation."
